= CLASSES

== Warrior
/* Fighter, Barbarian, Paladin */
Hoplites. Vikings. Legionaries. Immortals. Samurai. Eagle warriors. 
Thousands of years of real life history to pull inspiration from. 
Play this class to dish it out and take it. 

You have Advantage on tests: (Pick 3)
- Of strength. 
- Of stamina. 
- Of speed and mobility. 
- To spot and assess foes. 
- To make creative use of any weapon. 

You have Disadvantage on these tests (Pick 1): 
- Of stealth and subtlety
- To charm, entertain or lie
- To do something bookish

*Sturdy.* Add 5 to your injury limit. 

*Favored weapon.* One weapon in your possession is your favored weapon. You like it, maybe you named it. 
When you attack with it, also roll a six-sided die, preferably one with a unique color or style --- this is your _favored weapon die_. 

If it lands on 6, choose 1: 
- Introduce a relevant threat (Blurry vision for Dark, knocked over for Open, panicked for Dread, and so on)
- Turn one damage die to its highest possible value (6 for a d6, 8 for a d8, and so on). 

In downtime, practice with a different weapon to replace it as your favored one. 


== Wizard
/* Wizard, Mage, Sorcerer, Witch */
Magic is incredible and everyone else wishes they got the letter to go and study it. 
You're a wizard, hurray, so that is exactly what you do. 
Play this class to access a wide range of spells. 

You have Advantage on tests: (Pick 3)
- Of knowledge. 
- Of perceptiveness. 
- 
- To make creative use of a spell. 

You have Disadvantage on these tests (Pick 1):
- Of strength. 
- Of stamina. 
- Of speed and mobility. 


*Spellbook.*
Grab a stack of index cards, sticky notes or a small notebook to be your _spellbook_. 
In the fiction, your spellbook is an actual book, scroll, or tablet you can wield in one hand. 
When you wield a spellbook you can: 
 - Mark Stress to cast a spell you know, not included among your special actions. 
 - _Mark_ and _clear_ things in it. 

When rules allow you to *mark* something in the spellbook, write it down. 
When you *clear*, rip the sticky note, erase or cross it out in the notebook --- get rid of it. 

Arcane Bolt
Mark Stress, roll 1d6i per action spent. 
Mark this foe's name in your spellbook. Clear it to gain Advantage on a test related to a creature with this name. 



== Knave
/* Minor story benefit, good effect for 3-4/15 (~20-25%) rolls. */
Everyone loves a charming rogue, a brooding assassin, a morally grey mercenary with gallows humor. 
Play this class to get up to all sorts of shenanigans. 

*Suit up.*
Choose a suit: 
 - *Hearts*. Gain Advantage on tests to _charm into revealing secrets_. 
 - *Spades*. A dubious item, a worrying blood smear, a corpse --- there is always a convenient spot to bury evidence. 
 When you take a short time to "bury" something, only an extremely thorough search reveals anything. 
 - *Diamonds*. Whenever the heroes gain a sum of gold, gain 1 more or 20% more, whichever is higher. 
 - *Clubs.* Gain advantage on tests to _threaten with violence and guard doors_. 

*Lucky.*
Get a regular set of playing cards, or repurpose some index cards. 
Put together a small deck: Cards of your suit (Ace, 2 to 10, Knave, Queen, King) and two jokers, for a total of 15 cards. 
Match the Queen and King to two other heroes in your group. 
Remove one or both from the deck if there are fewer than two other heroes. 

Each time the play session begins, shuffle the deck then leave it facedown in front of you. 
*Whenever you roll a test, draw a card.* Reshuffle once they are all drawn. 

Ace: Turn a twelve-sided die of your choice to a 1. (It could be a 1 already.)
2-10: No effect. 
Knave: That's you. You automatically succeed, or put the knave back at the bottom of the deck if you already would succeed. 
Queen or King: Given you can describe a reasonable way in which the matched hero helps you succeed, gain Advantage. 
Joker: Turn a twelve-sided die of your choice to a 12. 


== Disciple
/* Cleric, Druid, Bard, Warlock */
You have faith in a deity, follow the teachings of a powerful patron, or see yourself as the herald of natural forces. 
You are a conduit for this outside power, or a student of it. 
Play this class to double down on a thematic character concept and tie it to the fantasy from the start. 

*Domains.* Choose two of the following elements that best reflect the nature of what you follow or worship. 
They are your two _domains_. 
For instance, a disciple of a goddess of harvests could choose Rest and Wild. 
A student of a bardic school could choose Bold and Lore. 

Bold - Awe, Passion. 
Arms - War, Authority. 
Magic - Magic, Strange. 
Fire - Zeal, Destruction. 
Hoax - Night, Dreams. 
Lore - Knowledge, Secrets. 
Rest - Healing, Death: Heal, deal damage to undead. 
Tinker - Craftsmanship, Civilization. 
Wild - Nature, Sea: Heal and damage mixed. 

*Mantras.*
Write 2 mantras that players can repeat or respond to, one per domain. Teach them to the other players. 

Tough. _When the going gets tough_: (targeted player) _The tough get going._
Magic. _Praise be to Jess_: (targeted player) _Matron of Magic and Tasteful Cupcakes._
Fire. _Fireball!_: (targeted player) _Taaa, ta ta, da ta da_
Arms. _Swords out for our Lord Aramde_: (other players thump their chests)

Any player-hero who responds gains Advantage on that test. 
You can say each mantra once, and must rest before you say it again. 

*Icon of Devotion.* 
Object you wield - a religious icon, a musical instrument, a sprig of mistletoe. It's not a weapon at all. 
When you wield it, reroll 1 and 2 on tests relevant to your domains. 


== Druid
This class may contain nuts. 
Seriously, if there are nut allergies at your table, substitute them with candy or play something else. 

Procure a bag of peanuts, cashews or other crunchy delight. 
If you can easily procure them each session, berries are also acceptable. 

You dispense blessings: metaphorical (advice) or physical (magical berries). 
Your nuts also count as threat tokens?

COMMANDER
Battle tactic: Swap two damage dice between allies that are close together OR swap two damage dice between foes OR grant an ally one additional action. 
Fall back!: Ally spends one action to clear one damage die. 
To me!: Allies that are far can get close to you. 

Reroll 1s on tests of Mettle. 


ROGUE
(+1d12) Dodge. 
Advantage to Mettle under ambient Cover, Dark or Fool. 
Evade. Mark stress to clear one damage die. 

Sneak attack. If you next action this turn deals any damage, also deal 1d12d if the target has Cover, Dark or Fool. 

ILLUSIONIST
Mirrored Trio: Mark Stress to gain 3 Images. Mark an Image to clear a damage die showing an odd result. 

ABJUROR
Magnetic field. (Passive) Whenever a damage die is rolled on you due to a metal weapon, arrowhead or similar, you can decide to reroll it once. 


== BATTLES

Sequence: 
1. Test of Mettle. 
2. Enemies act out their "suspended actions"
3. Hero with the highest Mettle result takes its turn; then identifies the next player to take its turn. And so on. 
Note: "Reactions" do not exist in the sense of being a distinct activity. Just spend all your actions. 
4. Settle. 

=== Test of Mettle
Special test: 
Fumble; 1 action
Manage; 2 actions (Mark Stress to turn into Success is possible)
Succeed; 3 actions
Difficulty is the foe with the highest difficulty, even if it is defeated in the scene. 

Can have a unique description, but is just "Be ready to fight" by default. 

==== Surprise
In the first round, each hero or foe gets one action, then Settle. 

=== Actions

Move: Get somewhere far. 

Interact: With your equipment or the environment. 

Defend: Reroll a damage die on you OR Shift a damage die from a close ally to you. 

Attack. Deal 1d4i close to you, with your fists or an improvised weapon. 
For the second or later attack made each round, roll the damage die twice and keep the lowest result. 
Weapons grant an Attack ability that overrides this one. 

Introduce a threat. The best suited one based on your description. 

Fire - Smash them with a burning torch. 
Water - Splash water at them.  
Dark - Throw pocket sand, blinding them. 
Trap - Lure them to a dangerous spot. 
Cold - Rip off their fur cloak. 
Cover - Place yourself behind cover from them. 
Open - Knock down cover around them. 
Dread - Scare or humiliate them. 
Blight - Let your poisoned weapon take effect. 
Fool - Make a feint. 

Clear a threat. Based on your description, which must be justified in the fiction and could be subject to a test when far fetched. 

Cast a spell. Some spells require more than one action to cast, though it is one by default. 

